useEffect lets you run code AFTER React renders your component. It's for side effects — things that reach outside the component: fetching data, setting up subscriptions, updating the document title, starting timers.

Think of it like this: React's job is to turn your state into UI. useEffect is for everything else that needs to happen as a consequence of that UI existing.

**Basic pattern:**
```jsx
useEffect(() => {
  // This runs AFTER the component renders
  document.title = `${count} items`

  return () => {
    // This runs when the component unmounts OR before the effect re-runs
    // Clean up: cancel timers, abort fetches, remove listeners
  }
}, [count]) // Only re-run when 'count' changes
```

**The dependency array controls WHEN it runs:**
- `[count]` — runs when `count` changes
- `[count, name]` — runs when either changes
- `[]` — runs once on mount, cleanup on unmount
- No array — runs after EVERY render (usually a mistake)

**The three gotchas that trip everyone up:**

1. **Missing dependencies** — if you use a variable inside the effect but don't include it in the deps array, you get stale values. React's exhaustive-deps lint rule catches this.

2. **Object/array deps** — `useEffect(() => {...}, [myObject])` re-runs every render because `{}` !== `{}` (reference equality). Fix: extract the specific primitive values you need, or wrap in useMemo.

3. **Missing cleanup** — if your effect creates a subscription, timer, or fetch, you MUST return a cleanup function. Without it, you get memory leaks and race conditions.

**Common mistake — using useEffect to derive state:**
```jsx
// BAD — useEffect to compute filtered list
const [filtered, setFiltered] = useState([])
useEffect(() => {
  setFiltered(items.filter(i => i.active))
}, [items])

// GOOD — just compute it directly
const filtered = items.filter(i => i.active)
// Or useMemo if the computation is expensive
const filtered = useMemo(() => items.filter(i => i.active), [items])
```

Rule of thumb: if you can compute something from existing state/props, you don't need useEffect. Just calculate it during render.

