This is a common CSS Grid issue. The cards have different heights because Grid rows default to auto height, which stretches to fit content.

**Fix 1: Equal height rows with `grid-template-rows: 1fr`**
Usually not what you want — this makes ALL rows the same height as the tallest card, wasting space.

**Fix 2: Fixed card height with overflow**
```css
.card {
  height: 300px; /* or min-height */
  overflow: hidden;
}
.card .description {
  display: -webkit-box;
  -webkit-line-clamp: 3;
  -webkit-box-orient: vertical;
  overflow: hidden;
}
```
This truncates long text with ellipsis. Good for uniform grids.

**Fix 3: Push footer to bottom with flexbox inside the card**
```css
.card {
  display: flex;
  flex-direction: column;
}
.card .content {
  flex: 1; /* takes remaining space */
}
.card .footer {
  margin-top: auto; /* pushed to bottom */
}
```
Cards can be different heights, but the footer (button, link, price) always aligns to the bottom. This is usually the best solution.

**Fix 4: Masonry layout (if varying heights is intentional)**
```css
.grid {
  columns: 3;
  column-gap: 24px;
}
.card {
  break-inside: avoid;
  margin-bottom: 24px;
}
```
Pinterest-style layout where cards stack without gaps.

