You're animating the wrong properties. The browser can only smoothly animate `transform` and `opacity` — they're GPU-composited and don't cause layout recalculation.

**Slow (triggers layout):**
```css
.card:hover { width: 320px; height: 200px; margin-top: -10px; left: 50px; }
```

**Fast (GPU composited):**
```css
.card:hover { transform: scale(1.05) translateY(-4px); }
```

**The rule:** Never animate `width`, `height`, `top`, `left`, `right`, `bottom`, `margin`, or `padding`. These trigger the browser's layout engine every frame (forced reflow). Instead:
- Moving → `transform: translate()`
- Resizing → `transform: scale()`
- Appearing → `opacity`
- Rotating → `transform: rotate()`

**Additional tips:**
```css
/* Hint to browser to prepare GPU layer */
.will-animate { will-change: transform; }

/* But remove it when not animating */
.card { will-change: auto; }
.card:hover { will-change: transform; }
```

Also check: are you running animations inside a scroll handler without `requestAnimationFrame`? And are you using `{ passive: true }` on scroll listeners? Both cause jank.

Add `flex-wrap: wrap` — flexbox is `nowrap` by default.

```css
/* Won't wrap (default): */
.container { display: flex; }

/* Will wrap: */
.container { display: flex; flex-wrap: wrap; gap: 16px; }
```

But wrapping alone doesn't control item width. You need to set a basis:

```css
/* 3 items per row on desktop, wrapping to fewer on mobile */
.item {
  flex: 1 1 300px; /* grow, shrink, minimum 300px before wrapping */
}
```

Or use CSS Grid, which handles this natively without flex-wrap:
```css
.container {
  display: grid;
  grid-template-columns: repeat(auto-fill, minmax(300px, 1fr));
  gap: 16px;
}
```

Grid `auto-fill` + `minmax` is usually cleaner than flex-wrap for card layouts. The items automatically wrap based on available width with no extra properties needed.

Glass morphism recipe:

```css
.glass-card {
  background: rgba(255, 255, 255, 0.05);  /* semi-transparent */
  backdrop-filter: blur(20px);              /* the blur effect */
  -webkit-backdrop-filter: blur(20px);      /* Safari */
  border: 1px solid rgba(255, 255, 255, 0.08); /* subtle edge */
  border-radius: 16px;
  padding: 32px;
}
```

**Requirements for glass to look good:**
1. There must be something behind the card (gradient, image, pattern). Glass on a solid color background looks the same as a solid card.
2. The background opacity should be low (0.03-0.08 for dark, 0.4-0.7 for light)
3. The blur should be high (12-24px) for frosted effect
4. Add a subtle border — without it the card edges disappear

**Light theme glass:**
```css
.glass-light {
  background: rgba(255, 255, 255, 0.6);
  backdrop-filter: blur(16px);
  border: 1px solid rgba(255, 255, 255, 0.3);
}
```

**Performance note:** `backdrop-filter` is GPU-intensive. Use it sparingly — on one or two elements, not on every card in a grid. On lower-end devices, it can cause lag.

**Fallback for unsupported browsers:**
```css
@supports not (backdrop-filter: blur(1px)) {
  .glass-card { background: rgba(20, 20, 30, 0.95); }
}
```

Refactor this imperative DOM manipulation:

const list = document.getElementById('list');
data.forEach(item => {
  const li = document.createElement('li');
  li.className = 'item';
  const title = document.createElement('h3');
  title.textContent = item.name;
  const desc = document.createElement('p');
  desc.textContent = item.description;
  li.appendChild(title);
  li.appendChild(desc);
  list.appendChild(li);
});

Replace imperative createElement/appendChild with declarative innerHTML template:

```javascript
const list = document.getElementById('list');
list.innerHTML = data.map(item => `
  <li class="item">
    <h3>${escapeHtml(item.name)}</h3>
    <p>${escapeHtml(item.description)}</p>
  </li>
`).join('');

// Always escape user data to prevent XSS
function escapeHtml(str) {
  const div = document.createElement('div');
  div.textContent = str;
  return div.innerHTML;
}
```

**Why this is better:**
- 4 lines instead of 12
- Template literals show the HTML structure visually
- Single DOM write (innerHTML) instead of N appendChild calls — much faster for large lists
- The `escapeHtml` function prevents XSS if data comes from user input

**For React, it's even simpler:**
```jsx
{data.map(item => (
  <li key={item.id} className="item">
    <h3>{item.name}</h3>
    <p>{item.description}</p>
  </li>
))}
```

**Performance note:** For very large lists (1000+ items), consider virtual scrolling (only render visible items) instead of rendering all at once. Libraries: react-window or @tanstack/react-virtual.

Refactor these repetitive event handlers:

const btn1 = document.getElementById('btn1');
const btn2 = document.getElementById('btn2');
const btn3 = document.getElementById('btn3');
btn1.addEventListener('click', () => { setActive(1); updateUI(1); });
btn2.addEventListener('click', () => { setActive(2); updateUI(2); });
btn3.addEventListener('click', () => { setActive(3); updateUI(3); });

Use event delegation — one listener on the parent instead of N on children:

**Option 1: Event delegation (best):**
```javascript
document.querySelector('.btn-group').addEventListener('click', (e) => {
  const btn = e.target.closest('[data-id]');
  if (!btn) return;

  const id = parseInt(btn.dataset.id);
  setActive(id);
  updateUI(id);
});
```
```html
<div class="btn-group">
  <button data-id="1">Option 1</button>
  <button data-id="2">Option 2</button>
  <button data-id="3">Option 3</button>
</div>
```

**Option 2: Loop (if you must attach individually):**
```javascript
document.querySelectorAll('[data-id]').forEach(btn => {
  btn.addEventListener('click', () => {
    const id = parseInt(btn.dataset.id);
    setActive(id);
    updateUI(id);
  });
});
```

**Why delegation is better:**
- One listener instead of N — better memory usage
- Works for dynamically added elements (new buttons don't need new listeners)
- Easier to clean up (remove one listener, not N)
- Uses `data-*` attributes as the source of truth instead of element IDs

The pattern: listen on the parent, use `e.target.closest()` to find the clicked child, read data from `data-*` attributes.

